## Diagnosis

The symptom ‚Äî active label appearing on the **right** side while hover labels appear on the **left** ‚Äî points to a **conflicting coordinate-space assumption** between the two label systems.

### What's almost certainly happening

The hover labels use `position: absolute` anchored to a **parent container that is already right-edge-aligned** (the rail/gutter element itself), so `right: 100%` (or a fixed negative `left`) naturally projects them leftward into the viewport.

The active label is being positioned relative to a **different ancestor** ‚Äî likely the viewport or a wrapper with `position: relative` set further up the tree ‚Äî so its `left`/`right` values resolve against a wider coordinate space, pushing it off-screen to the right.

Changing the anchor from the tick to the notch container didn't help because **both are inside the same wrong positioning context**; you moved the anchor but kept the same broken parent chain.

The classic anti-pattern here is **AP-072 (Mixed Positioning Contexts)**: one component establishes a `position: relative` root at a high DOM level while a sibling component assumes a narrower ancestor, causing both to render but diverge in screen coordinates.

---

## Root Cause

```
<ScrollSpyRail>               ‚Üê position: relative (rail gutter, right edge)
  <RailTrack>
    <Notch key={section}>     ‚Üê position: absolute, top: N%
      <Tick />                ‚Üê inner element, no positioning
      <HoverLabel />          ‚Üê position: absolute, right: 100%  ‚úì correct
    </Notch>
  </RailTrack>

  <ActiveLabel />             ‚Üê rendered HERE, outside <Notch>
                              ‚Üê but positioned relative to ScrollSpyRail
                              ‚Üê OR teleported via a portal to <body>
                              ‚Üê so right: 100% means right of the RAIL not the notch
</ScrollSpyRail>
```

The active label is rendered as a **sibling of the track** (or portalled), not as a child of the active `<Notch>`. Its `top` is computed in JS from `getBoundingClientRect()` and applied inline, but `right: 100%` (or `left: -Xpx`) is computed against the wrong box.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 ‚Äî Locate the ScrollSpy rail component

```
src/components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyRail.tsx   (or .jsx)
src/components/ScrollSpy/ActiveLabel.tsx
src/components/ScrollSpy/Notch.tsx
```

### Step 2 ‚Äî Move `<ActiveLabel>` inside the active `<Notch>`

The **only reliable fix** is to render the active label from inside the same `<Notch>` that renders the hover label. They must share the same `position: relative` ancestor so that `right: 100%` resolves identically for both.

**`Notch.tsx` ‚Äî before (broken pattern)**

```tsx
// Notch.tsx
export function Notch({ section, isActive }: NotchProps) {
  return (
    <div
      className="notch"
      style={{ position: 'absolute', top: `${section.progress * 100}%` }}
    >
      <Tick />
      <HoverLabel label={section.label} />
      {/* ActiveLabel rendered elsewhere ‚Äî WRONG */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

**`Notch.tsx` ‚Äî after (fixed)**

```tsx
// Notch.tsx
export function Notch({ section, isActive }: NotchProps) {
  return (
    <div
      // This element is the single positioning root for BOTH labels.
      // position:absolute is set by the parent track mapper.
      className="relative flex items-center"
    >
      <Tick isActive={isActive} />

      {/*
        Both labels are absolutely positioned children of THIS element.
        right: 100% on either label means "left edge of the Notch box",
        which is always the rail's left edge ‚Äî exactly where we want them.
      */}
      <HoverLabel label={section.label} />
      {isActive && <ActiveLabel label={section.label} />}
    </div>
  )
}
```

**`ActiveLabel.tsx` ‚Äî ensure identical positioning to `HoverLabel`**

```tsx
// ActiveLabel.tsx
export function ActiveLabel({ label }: { label: string }) {
  return (
    <span
      className={[
        // Mirror every layout class from HoverLabel ‚Äî same anchor, same side
        'absolute',
        'right-full',          // ‚Üê projects LEFT of the notch, into the gutter
        'pr-3',                // same gap as hover label
        'whitespace-nowrap',
        'text-right',
        // Vertical centering within the notch row
        'top-1/2',
        '-translate-y-1/2',
        // Visual differentiation (active state)
        'text-sm',
        'font-semibold',
        'text-foreground',     // or your active token
        'pointer-events-none',
      ].join(' ')}
    >
      {label}
    </span>
  )
}
```

**`HoverLabel.tsx` ‚Äî confirm it matches (reference)**

```tsx
// HoverLabel.tsx  ‚Äî should already look like this
export function HoverLabel({ label }: { label: string }) {
  return (
    <span
      className={[
        'absolute',
        'right-full',          // same anchor point
        'pr-3',
        'whitespace-nowrap',
        'text-right',
        'top-1/2',
        '-translate-y-1/2',
        'text-sm',
        'font-medium',
        'text-muted-foreground',
        'opacity-0',
        'group-hover:opacity-100',
        'transition-opacity',
        'pointer-events-none',
      ].join(' ')}
    >
      {label}
    </span>
  )
}
```

### Step 3 ‚Äî Remove the orphaned `<ActiveLabel>` from the rail root

```tsx
// ScrollSpyRail.tsx ‚Äî before
export function ScrollSpyRail({ sections, activeId }: Props) {
  const activeSection = sections.find(s => s.id === activeId)

  return (
    <nav className="fixed right-0 top-0 h-full" style={{ position: 'relative' }}>
      <RailTrack sections={sections} activeId={activeId} />

      {/* DELETE THIS ‚Äî it's the root cause */}
      {activeSection && (
        <ActiveLabel
          label={activeSection.label}
          style={{ top: computedTopPx }}   // JS-computed, wrong context
        />
      )}
    </nav>
  )
}
```

```tsx
// ScrollSpyRail.tsx ‚Äî after
export function ScrollSpyRail({ sections, activeId }: Props) {
  return (
    <nav className="fixed right-0 top-0 h-full">
      <RailTrack sections={sections} activeId={activeId} />
      {/* ActiveLabel now lives inside each Notch ‚Äî no orphan here */}
    </nav>
  )
}
```

### Step 4 ‚Äî If you're using a CSS transition to animate the active label vertically

Instead of animating `top` on a single shared element (which requires it to be at the rail level), animate `opacity` + `scale` on the per-notch instance:

```tsx
// ActiveLabel.tsx ‚Äî with transition
<span
  className={[
    'absolute right-full pr-3',
    'whitespace-nowrap text-right',
    'top-1/2 -translate-y-1/2',
    'text-sm font-semibold text-foreground',
    // Fade-in when notch becomes active
    'transition-opacity duration-200',
    isActive ? 'opacity-100' : 'opacity-0 pointer-events-none',
  ].join(' ')}
>
  {label}
</span>
```

This removes the need for any JS position computation entirely.

---

## Principle

> **A positioned element's percentage-based or `right: 100%` offsets resolve against its nearest `position` ancestor ‚Äî not the element you intend visually.**  
> When two sibling UI elements must align to the same edge, they must share the same `position: relative` root. Rendering one as a child of that root and the other as a child of a higher ancestor creates an invisible seam that no amount of anchor-swapping inside the wrong subtree will close (AP-072).  
> The invariant: **if two things must line up, they must live in the same coordinate space.**
